{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501009"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:21:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:21:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1705"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1705","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1705"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.09,0.04,0.02,0.7]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1705"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40090"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1705","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1705"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1705"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24807"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"456"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1035"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27419"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40090","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/40090"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 66-year-old sheep farmer presents with a three month history of epigastric discomfort, his symptoms being worse after meals. His medical history includes hypertension and ischaemic heart disease. He takes perindopril, simvastatin and aspirin. He drinks about three cans of beer a day. His blood pressure is 134/86 mmHg, pulse 84/min and temperature 37.2C. Apart from some mild epigastric tenderness, the rest of the physical examination is unremarkable. A CT scan is performed and a representative image shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one the following is the most likely explanation for the radiological findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pancreatic pseudocyst","Gastrointestinal stromal tumour","Gallstone","Abdominal aortic aneurysm","Hydatid cyst"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere is a cystic lesion with a calcified rim in segments II/III of the liver. Such an appearance is characteristic of an \u003Cstrong\u003Ehydatid cyst\u003C/strong\u003E. The lesion is cystic, thus excluding gallstones and a gastrointestinal stromal tumour. The abdominal aorta is visible on the scan and is well away from this lesion. Even if this lesion was adjacent to the pancreas, the rim of calcification implies chronicity and would exclude a pseudocyst.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHydatid disease used to be relatively common amongst the sheep farming community in Australia and is still endemic in various parts of the world, particularly the Middle East and Mediterranean countries. The primary host of the tapeworm, Echinococcus granulosus, is the dog and other similar carnivores. The tapeworm lives in the gut and eggs are shed into the faeces. The eggs are ingested by the intermediate host - typically a grazing animal - where they hatch and spread to the lungs, liver, muscles and other structure. There the larval cestodes develop into cysts. The cycle is completed when the infected animal is eaten by a dog or similar creature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMan may inadvertently become infected (an intermediate host) by ingesting the eggs - eg after stroking the fur of an infected dog. In most cases such infection does not cause any symptoms and the presence of the cyst only become apparent during some sort of imaging procedure, when the calcified (long-standing) cyst is seen. With better standards of hygiene and deworming of dogs, hydatid disease has become less of a problem in this country, but cysts are still being found incidentally, particularly in individuals with a rural background. These cysts are most characteristically found in the liver, but the spleen and  lungs are other relatively common sites. Sometimes small cysts can be seen within the main cyst - so-called \u0027daughter cysts.\u0027\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hydatid cysts should always be considered in case of isolated cysts with a calcified rim."],"references":["Higuita NIA, Brunetti E, McCloskey C. Cystic Echinococcosis. J Clin Microbiol 2016; 54:518-23."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24807"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1705"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18355"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18355","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18355"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9072caa3-ca81-4290-9b36-18154845d426.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9072caa3-ca81-4290-9b36-18154845d426.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":508,"height":429}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24807","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/24807"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-10-29T17:58:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2023-10-29T17:58:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1705"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40090"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/